---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Header from '../../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../../components/Footer.astro';
---

<Layout title="Custom Software vs Off-the-Shelf: Which Is Right for Your Business? | Etacom Technology" description="We compare the pros and cons of building custom software versus using ready-made solutions.">
  <Header homeLink="/" />

  <main>
    <section class="page-hero">
      <div class="page-hero-bg"></div>
      <div class="container page-hero-content">
        <a href="/blog" class="blog-back">&larr; Back to Blog</a>
        <span class="blog-category">Software Development</span>
        <h1 class="page-hero-title">Custom Software vs Off-the-Shelf: Which Is Right for Your Business?</h1>
        <p class="page-hero-desc">February 2026</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <div class="container blog-content">
        <p>We compare the pros and cons of building custom software versus using ready-made solutions, and help you decide what fits your needs and budget.</p>

        <h2>Off-the-Shelf: Quick and Affordable</h2>
        <p>Ready-made software can be deployed immediately. Products like QuickBooks, Microsoft 365, or generic POS systems come with proven features and regular updates. For standard business needs, this is often the fastest path to going digital.</p>

        <h2>Custom Software: Built for You</h2>
        <p>When your business processes are unique — multi-branch inventory with complex approval workflows, specialized CRM requirements, or industry-specific regulations — off-the-shelf software often falls short. Custom software is built around your exact needs, not the other way around.</p>

        <h2>The Hidden Cost of Off-the-Shelf</h2>
        <p>Generic software often requires workarounds, manual data entry between systems, and multiple subscriptions. Over time, these hidden costs can exceed the price of a custom solution.</p>

        <h2>When to Go Custom</h2>
        <p>Consider custom software when: your workflow is complex and unique, you need integration between multiple systems, you're paying for multiple tools that don't talk to each other, or your team spends hours on manual data entry.</p>

        <h2>The Hybrid Approach</h2>
        <p>Many businesses find success with a hybrid approach: use off-the-shelf tools for standard functions (email, accounting) and build custom software for core differentiators (inventory, CRM, operations).</p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>

  <Footer />
</Layout>

<style>
  .page-hero { position: relative; padding: 140px 0 80px; overflow: hidden; }
  .page-hero-bg { position: absolute; inset: 0; background: var(--dark); }
  .page-hero-content { position: relative; z-index: 1; }
  .page-hero-title { font-family: var(--font-heading); font-size: clamp(1.75rem, 4vw, 2.5rem); font-weight: 800; color: var(--white); margin-bottom: 12px; }
  .page-hero-desc { font-size: 1rem; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.6); }
  .blog-back { display: inline-block; font-size: 0.875rem; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.6); text-decoration: none; margin-bottom: 16px; transition: color 0.2s; }
  .blog-back:hover { color: var(--white); }
  .blog-category { display: inline-block; font-size: 0.75rem; font-weight: 600; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.05em; color: var(--primary); background: rgba(220,38,38,0.1); padding: 4px 12px; border-radius: 50px; margin-bottom: 12px; }
  .blog-content { max-width: 720px; }
  .blog-content h2 { font-family: var(--font-heading); font-size: 1.25rem; font-weight: 600; color: var(--dark); margin: 32px 0 12px; }
  .blog-content p { font-size: 1rem; color: var(--text); line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 16px; }
</style>
